= The Fractured Fascist Threat
                                                                                    
The fascist movement has splintered into competing factions: Hitler's rump NSDAP (34 seats), Strasser's Black Front (28 seats), and Röhm's SA-backed politicians (19 seats). Combined they'd be formidable—81 seats and significant street presence. Divided, they're weakened.
Internal competition: The three factions spend as much energy fighting each other as opposing the Republic. Hitler denounces Strasser as a "socialist traitor." Strasser calls Hitler a "capitalist tool." Röhm dismisses both as "talkers." They compete for recruits, resources, and ideological territory.

We have perhaps 12-18 months before the situation clarifies. Either fascism consolidates around a winning faction, or we use this time to strengthen the Republic enough to survive whatever comes next.
This is our chance. We cannot waste it.
                                                                                    
@conclude: Conclude the assessment.
                                                                                    
@conclude
                                                                                    
The intelligence briefing concludes. Our analysts have provided their assessment of the fascist threat in its various forms. Now the question becomes: what will we do about it?
[? if fascist_threat_level >= 4 : The threat is severe and immediate. Every month of inaction increases the danger. ?]
[? if fascist_threat_level == 3 : The threat is serious but not yet overwhelming. We have time to act, but not much. ?]
[? if fascist_threat_level == 2 : The threat is manageable for now, but could escalate rapidly if conditions change. ?]
The fate of the Republic may depend on our next moves.
                                                                                    
@return_assess
